<BaseLayout title="optimisationblindness.org">
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="lede">
      <strong>Optimisation blindness</strong> is the property of an automated environment in which locally rational optimisation, performed by multiple systems in parallel, aggregates into outcomes that no individual system can detect — because the relevant signals are absent from any one objective function.
    </p>
    <p class="hierarchy">
      The work proceeds at three levels. <strong>The concept</strong> names what optimisation cannot see. <strong>Two measurement frameworks operationalise it:</strong> <a href="/revemo">RevEmo</a> at the scale of the hotel property, <a href="/deqi">DEQI</a> at the scale of the tourism city. <strong>Essays and working papers</strong> develop the implications.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <p class="section-label">Recent</p>
    <ul class="recent-list">
      <li>
        <em><a href="/deqi">Optimisation Blindness at the Destination Level (DEQI)</a>.</em>
        Working paper, <em>International Journal of Tourism Cities</em>. Submitted, pending preprint.
      </li>
      <li>
        <em><a href="/revemo">Revenue per Emotional Moment (RevEmo)</a>.</em>
        Working paper, <em>International Journal of Hospitality Management</em>. Under review.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
